<taxonomicName box="[295,467,1908,1930]" class="Insecta" family="Psychodidae" genus="Lepidiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="88" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="olgae" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[295,467,1908,1930]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="88">Lepidiella olgae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[480,568,1909,1930]" pageId="3" pageNumber="88">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[480,568,1909,1930]" pageId="3" pageNumber="88" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
male holotype. (A) head; (B) base of antenna: scape, pedicel and three basal flagellomeres; (C) flagellomeres 12, 13 and 14; (D) palpus; (E) wing; female: (F) ventral; male terminalia: (G) ventral: epandrium, cerci and hypoproct; (H) dorsal; (I) cercus. Escale bars: Figs 2A, 2E = 0.25 mm, Figs 2B, 2C, 2D, 2F = 0.06 mm, Figs 2G, 2H, 2I = 0.12 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="89" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1406]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,151,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">Description.</emphasis>
Male 
<typeStatus box="[415,517,151,175]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">holotype</typeStatus>
. Head (
<figureCitation box="[601,667,151,175]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1908,1931]" captionTargetBox="[222,1412,438,1888]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[180,1416,435,1889]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Lepidiella olgae sp. nov. male holotype. (A) head; (B) base of antenna: scape, pedicel and three basal flagellomeres; (C) flagellomeres 12, 13 and 14; (D) palpus; (E) wing; female: (F) ventral; male terminalia: (G) ventral: epandrium, cerci and hypoproct; (H) dorsal; (I) cercus. Escale bars: Figs 2 A, 2 E = 0.25 mm, Figs 2 B, 2 C, 2 D, 2 F = 0.06 mm, Figs 2 G, 2 H, 2 I = 0.12 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/284306/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">
Fig. 
<number box="[653,667,151,175]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A) without corniculum. Vertex dorsally expanded. Eyes separated by 2.0 facet diameters; eye bridge with four facet rows; interocular suture inverted Y-shaped; frons with hair patch not divided at center, extending dorsally and reaching the interocular suture. Scape approximately the same length as pedicel, without internal protuberances (
<figureCitation box="[619,692,260,284]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1908,1931]" captionTargetBox="[222,1412,438,1888]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[180,1416,435,1889]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Lepidiella olgae sp. nov. male holotype. (A) head; (B) base of antenna: scape, pedicel and three basal flagellomeres; (C) flagellomeres 12, 13 and 14; (D) palpus; (E) wing; female: (F) ventral; male terminalia: (G) ventral: epandrium, cerci and hypoproct; (H) dorsal; (I) cercus. Escale bars: Figs 2 A, 2 E = 0.25 mm, Figs 2 B, 2 C, 2 D, 2 F = 0.06 mm, Figs 2 G, 2 H, 2 I = 0.12 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/284306/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">
Fig. 
<number box="[676,692,260,284]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
B). Flagellum with 
<number box="[921,949,260,284]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="14.0">14</number>
flagellomeres; first flagellomere fusiform (
<figureCitation box="[159,225,295,319]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1903,1926]" captionTargetBox="[176,1392,476,1877]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[175,1411,473,1877]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Arisemus rubeni sp. nov. male holotype. (A) head; (B) base of antenna: scape, pedicel and four basal flagellomeres; (C) flagellomeres 11, 12 and 13; (D) palpus; (E) wing; (F) wing jugum; (G) sensory organ of antepronotum; male terminalia (spi = anterior spiracle); (H) dorsal; (I) epandrium, cerci and hypoproct. Escale bars: Figs 1 A, 1 E, 1 F = 0.25 mm, Figs 1 B, 1 C, 1 D, 1 G = 0.06 mm, Figs 1 H, 1 I = 0.12 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/284305/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">
Fig. 
<number box="[214,225,295,319]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
B); flagellomeres 
<number box="[436,492,295,319]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="7.5" valueMax="13.0" valueMin="2.0">2–13</number>
fusiform with short internodes (
<figureCitation box="[869,946,295,319]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1903,1926]" captionTargetBox="[176,1392,476,1877]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[175,1411,473,1877]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Arisemus rubeni sp. nov. male holotype. (A) head; (B) base of antenna: scape, pedicel and four basal flagellomeres; (C) flagellomeres 11, 12 and 13; (D) palpus; (E) wing; (F) wing jugum; (G) sensory organ of antepronotum; male terminalia (spi = anterior spiracle); (H) dorsal; (I) epandrium, cerci and hypoproct. Escale bars: Figs 1 A, 1 E, 1 F = 0.25 mm, Figs 1 B, 1 C, 1 D, 1 G = 0.06 mm, Figs 1 H, 1 I = 0.12 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/284305/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">
Figs. 
<number box="[935,946,295,319]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
B, C); flagellomere 
<number box="[1182,1210,295,319]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="14.0">14</number>
with apiculus (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1903,1926]" captionTargetBox="[176,1392,476,1877]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[175,1411,473,1877]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Arisemus rubeni sp. nov. male holotype. (A) head; (B) base of antenna: scape, pedicel and four basal flagellomeres; (C) flagellomeres 11, 12 and 13; (D) palpus; (E) wing; (F) wing jugum; (G) sensory organ of antepronotum; male terminalia (spi = anterior spiracle); (H) dorsal; (I) epandrium, cerci and hypoproct. Escale bars: Figs 1 A, 1 E, 1 F = 0.25 mm, Figs 1 B, 1 C, 1 D, 1 G = 0.06 mm, Figs 1 H, 1 I = 0.12 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/284305/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">
Fig. 
<number box="[151,162,332,356]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
C); pair of digitate ascoids on each flagellomere (
<figureCitation box="[768,837,332,356]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1903,1926]" captionTargetBox="[176,1392,476,1877]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[175,1411,473,1877]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Arisemus rubeni sp. nov. male holotype. (A) head; (B) base of antenna: scape, pedicel and four basal flagellomeres; (C) flagellomeres 11, 12 and 13; (D) palpus; (E) wing; (F) wing jugum; (G) sensory organ of antepronotum; male terminalia (spi = anterior spiracle); (H) dorsal; (I) epandrium, cerci and hypoproct. Escale bars: Figs 1 A, 1 E, 1 F = 0.25 mm, Figs 1 B, 1 C, 1 D, 1 G = 0.06 mm, Figs 1 H, 1 I = 0.12 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/284305/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">
Fig. 
<number box="[826,837,332,356]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
B) except for the last three. Ratio of palpomeres: 1.0: 
<number box="[191,231,367,391]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="2.2">2.2</number>
: 
<number box="[235,275,367,391]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="2.2">2.2</number>
:3.0; last palpomere striated (
<figureCitation box="[598,661,367,391]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1903,1926]" captionTargetBox="[176,1392,476,1877]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[175,1411,473,1877]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Arisemus rubeni sp. nov. male holotype. (A) head; (B) base of antenna: scape, pedicel and four basal flagellomeres; (C) flagellomeres 11, 12 and 13; (D) palpus; (E) wing; (F) wing jugum; (G) sensory organ of antepronotum; male terminalia (spi = anterior spiracle); (H) dorsal; (I) epandrium, cerci and hypoproct. Escale bars: Figs 1 A, 1 E, 1 F = 0.25 mm, Figs 1 B, 1 C, 1 D, 1 G = 0.06 mm, Figs 1 H, 1 I = 0.12 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/284305/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">
Fig. 
<number box="[650,661,367,391]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
D).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1406]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">
Wing (
<figureCitation box="[275,337,404,428]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1903,1926]" captionTargetBox="[176,1392,476,1877]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[175,1411,473,1877]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Arisemus rubeni sp. nov. male holotype. (A) head; (B) base of antenna: scape, pedicel and four basal flagellomeres; (C) flagellomeres 11, 12 and 13; (D) palpus; (E) wing; (F) wing jugum; (G) sensory organ of antepronotum; male terminalia (spi = anterior spiracle); (H) dorsal; (I) epandrium, cerci and hypoproct. Escale bars: Figs 1 A, 1 E, 1 F = 0.25 mm, Figs 1 B, 1 C, 1 D, 1 G = 0.06 mm, Figs 1 H, 1 I = 0.12 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/284305/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">
Fig. 
<number box="[327,337,404,428]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
E) 
<number box="[375,410,404,428]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="2.8">2.8</number>
times longer than broad; costal cell darker than rest of wing membrane; radial fork distal to medial fork; R 
<number box="[314,322,455,469]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="4.0">4</number>
ending at wing tip.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1406]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">
Male terminalia (
<figureCitation box="[392,469,479,503]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1908,1931]" captionTargetBox="[222,1412,438,1888]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[180,1416,435,1889]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Lepidiella olgae sp. nov. male holotype. (A) head; (B) base of antenna: scape, pedicel and three basal flagellomeres; (C) flagellomeres 12, 13 and 14; (D) palpus; (E) wing; female: (F) ventral; male terminalia: (G) ventral: epandrium, cerci and hypoproct; (H) dorsal; (I) cercus. Escale bars: Figs 2 A, 2 E = 0.25 mm, Figs 2 B, 2 C, 2 D, 2 F = 0.06 mm, Figs 2 G, 2 H, 2 I = 0.12 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/284306/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">
Figs. 
<number box="[456,469,479,503]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
G, H, I): hypandrium stripe-like with apical microtrichia; gonocoxite 
<number box="[1245,1280,479,503]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="0.4">0.4</number>
times as long as gonostyle; gonostylus with 
<number box="[501,515,514,538]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="2.0">2</number>
/ 
<number box="[525,537,514,538]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="3.0">3</number>
apical bare and 
<number box="[732,742,514,538]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[753,767,514,538]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="3.0">3</number>
basal inflated, with basal patch of setal alveoli; aedeagus symmetrical, bifid, V-shaped; two pairs of parameres, external pair shorter than internal; internal parameres knifelike, ending in pointed apex, not bifurcated; ejaculatory apodeme dorsoventrally flatened; gonocoxal bridge not expanded anteriorly; epandrium 
<number box="[517,552,623,647]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="1.5">1.5</number>
times wider than long, with two foramina; cercus with 
<number box="[1178,1206,623,647]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="14.0">14</number>
tenacula; hypoproct with apical micropilosity.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1406]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">
Comments. The Neotropical genus 
<taxonomicName box="[602,716,695,719]" class="Insecta" family="Psychodidae" genus="Lepidiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[602,716,695,719]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">Lepidiella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
currently comprises 
<number box="[956,984,695,719]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="13.0">13</number>
species and is known from 
<collectingCountry box="[1305,1432,695,719]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[151,269,730,754]" name="Nicaragua" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">Nicaragua</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[282,374,731,754]" name="Panama" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">Panama</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[387,500,730,754]" name="Colombia" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[513,567,731,754]" name="Peru" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">Peru</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[580,665,730,754]" name="Bolivia" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[679,747,730,754]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(the states of São Paulo and Espírito Santo) and from 
<collectingCountry name="Saint Lucia" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">Saint Lucia</collectingCountry>
in the Caribbean (Ibáñez-Bernal 
<number box="[608,667,767,791]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="2010.0">2010</number>
, Bravo &amp; Santos 
<number box="[879,939,767,791]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="2011.0">2011</number>
). 
<taxonomicName box="[962,1076,767,791]" class="Insecta" family="Psychodidae" genus="Lepidiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[962,1076,767,791]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">Lepidiella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by having the vertex dorsally expanded, R 
<number box="[466,474,818,832]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="4.0">4</number>
ending at the wing tip, gonocoxal apodemes not expanded anteriorly, and males with multiple tenacula (Bravo &amp; Santos 
<number box="[547,607,841,865]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="2011.0">2011</number>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1406]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">
Three morphological species groups can be recognized in 
<taxonomicName box="[851,965,877,901]" class="Insecta" family="Psychodidae" genus="Lepidiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[851,965,877,901]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">Lepidiella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: 
<number box="[980,992,877,901]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="1.0">1</number>
) species with scape and pedicel having approximately the same lengths and head without corniculi, characteristics observed in many other 
<taxonomicName box="[1257,1402,913,937]" class="Insecta" family="Psychodidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Psychodinae">Psychodinae</taxonomicName>
; 
<number box="[1413,1428,913,937]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="2.0">2</number>
) species with scape equal to or more than 
<number box="[621,656,949,973]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="1.5">1.5</number>
times the length of pedicel, without internal protuberances and head with corniculi; 
<number box="[322,336,985,1009]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="3.0">3</number>
) species with scape equal to or more than 
<number box="[813,848,985,1009]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" value="1.5">1.5</number>
times the length of pedicel, head with corniculi.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1406]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">
The new species 
<taxonomicName box="[393,576,1022,1046]" class="Insecta" family="Psychodidae" genus="Lepidiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="olgae">
<emphasis box="[393,576,1022,1046]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">Lepidiella olgae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is included in the first group (species with scape and pedicel approximately the same length, head without corniculi), characteristics shared by only two other species, both from 
<collectingCountry box="[1360,1433,1057,1081]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">Brazil</collectingCountry>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="Bravo" authorityName="Bravo" box="[151,432,1094,1118]" class="Insecta" family="Psychodidae" genus="Lepidiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosa">
<emphasis box="[151,357,1094,1118]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">Lepidiella spinosa</emphasis>
Bravo
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Bravo &amp; Santos." authorityName="Bravo &amp; Santos." box="[487,908,1093,1118]" class="Insecta" family="Psychodidae" genus="Lepidiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flabellata">
<emphasis box="[487,714,1094,1118]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">Lepidiella flabellata</emphasis>
Bravo &amp; Santos.
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1406]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">
<taxonomicName box="[199,378,1129,1153]" class="Insecta" family="Psychodidae" genus="Lepidiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="olgae">
<emphasis box="[199,378,1129,1153]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">Lepidiella olgae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be differentiated from 
<taxonomicName box="[677,811,1129,1153]" class="Insecta" family="Psychodidae" genus="Lepidiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flabellata">
<emphasis box="[677,811,1129,1153]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">L. flabellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the number tenacula, 
<quantity box="[1090,1146,1129,1153]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.556" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" unit="in" value="14.0">14 in</quantity>
the new species and 
<quantity box="[1380,1436,1129,1153]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.318" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" unit="in" value="17.0">17 in</quantity>
the latter, and by the shapes of the internal parameres, bifurcated in 
<taxonomicName box="[888,1021,1166,1190]" class="Insecta" family="Psychodidae" genus="Lepidiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flabellata">
<emphasis box="[888,1021,1166,1190]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">L. flabellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and blade-shaped in the new species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1406]" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">
The male terminalia of 
<taxonomicName box="[476,571,1201,1225]" class="Insecta" family="Psychodidae" genus="Lepidiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="olgae">
<emphasis box="[476,571,1201,1225]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">L. olgae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[633,752,1202,1225]" class="Insecta" family="Psychodidae" genus="Lepidiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosa">
<emphasis box="[633,752,1202,1225]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">L. spinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished by the shape of ejaculatory apodeme (paddle-shaped in the new species and narrower in 
<taxonomicName box="[734,872,1238,1262]" class="Insecta" family="Psychodidae" genus="Lepidiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flabellata">
<emphasis box="[734,872,1238,1262]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">L. flabellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and by the relative sizes of the parameres (with the external paramere in 
<taxonomicName box="[436,574,1273,1297]" class="Insecta" family="Psychodidae" genus="Lepidiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flabellata">
<emphasis box="[436,574,1273,1297]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">L. flabellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
terminating near the apex of the internal paramere and ending in a pointed apex, and a shorter external paramere in the new species, ending at the center of the internal paramere, with apex plumose). Another difference between these two species are the colors of their costal cells, darker in the new species and normal in 
<taxonomicName box="[401,538,1382,1406]" class="Insecta" family="Psychodidae" genus="Lepidiella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="89" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flabellata">
<emphasis box="[401,538,1382,1406]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="89">L. flabellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
